PRESIDENT Jacob Zuma and five people associated with him, including his four wives, are among the 17 South Africans who get VIP protection from the South African Police Service (SAPS).The specialist protection unit also protected 65 foreign dignitaries protected during the 2016-17 financial year. The unit also looked after seven foreign dignitaries between April 1, 2017 and May 10, 2017.The four presidential wives receiving specialist protection are Gertrude Sizakele Khumalo, known as Ma Khumalo, Nompumelelo Ntuli, also known as Ma Ntuli, Tobeka Madiba and Bongi Ngema, also known as Ma Ngema.The other person associated with the president, who is a recipient of SAPS protection, is his former wife and past African Union chairperson, Nkosazana Dlamini Zuma.Also in this group of 17, Police Minister Fikile Mbalula said, are former presidents FW de Klerk, Thabo Mbeki and Kgalema Motlanthe. Mbalula gave details in reply to a question from DA member of Parliament Zach Mbhele, who asked for details of about South Africans under VIP protection.Mbhele wanted to know how many people were protected in the 2016-17 financial year, as well as in the period starting on April 1 this year.Those South Africans, who are also the beneficiaries of VIP protection, are deputy president Cyril Ramaphosa, his wife, former deputy presidents Phumzile Mlambo-Ngcuka and Baleka Mbete, Nelson Mandela s widow Gra a Machel and the director-general in the presidency, Cassius Lubisi.DENNIS CRUYWAGEN